.TH "POINTEREVENT.PERSISTENTDEVICEID" "3JS" "July 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
PointerEvent.persistentDeviceId \- PointerEvent: persistentDeviceId
property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]persistentDeviceId\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]PointerEvent\f[R] interface is a unique identifier for the
pointing device generating the \f[CR]PointerEvent\f[R].
This provides a secure, reliable way to identify multiple pointing
devices (such as pens) interacting with the screen simultaneously.
.PP
A \f[CR]persistentDeviceId\f[R] persists for the lifetime of a browsing
session.
To avoid the risk of fingerprinting/tracking, pointing devices are
assigned a new \f[CR]persistentDeviceId\f[R] at the start of each
session.
.PP
Pointer events whose generating device could not be identified are
assigned a \f[CR]persistentDeviceId\f[R] value of \f[CR]0\f[R].
.SH VALUE
An integer, or \f[CR]0\f[R] if the device generating the
\f[CR]PointerEvent\f[R] could not be identified.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Due to digitizer and pointing device hardware
constraints, a \f[CR]persistentDeviceId\f[R] may not be available for
all pointer events, particularly with older hardware.
For example, the pointing device might not report its hardware ID to the
digitizer in time for \f[CR]pointerdown\f[R] to receive a
\f[CR]persistentDeviceId\f[R]: it may initially be \f[CR]0\f[R] and
change to a valid value for later events in the stroke.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Assign color for each persistentDeviceId
Assuming the following HTML:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]canvas\f[R] id=\(dqinking\-surface\(dq width=\(dq1280\(dq height=\(dq720\(dq></\f[B]canvas\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
The following JavaScript assigns a different inking color to up to three
unique pointers interacting with a canvas:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] colorBlue = 0;
\f[B]const\f[R] colorGreen = 1;
\f[B]const\f[R] colorYellow = 2;
\f[B]const\f[R] colors = [colorBlue, colorGreen, colorYellow];

\f[B]const\f[R] pointerToColorMap = \f[B]new\f[R] Map();
\f[B]let\f[R] colorAssignmentIndex = 0;

\f[B]const\f[R] canvas = document.querySelector(\(dq#inking\-surface\(dq);

\f[I]// Listen for a pointerdown event and map the persistentDeviceId to a color\f[R]
\f[I]// if it exists and has not been mapped yet\f[R]
canvas.addEventListener(\(dqpointerdown\(dq, (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (e.persistentDeviceId && !pointerToColorMap.has(e.persistentDeviceId)) {
    pointerToColorMap.set(e.persistentDeviceId, colors[colorAssignmentIndex]);

    \f[I]// Bump the color assignment index and loop back over if needed\f[R]
    colorAssignmentIndex = (colorAssignmentIndex + 1) % colors.length;
  }
});

\f[I]// Listen for a \(gapointermove\(ga and get the color assigned to this pointer\f[R]
\f[I]// if persistentDeviceId exists and the pointer has been color mapped\f[R]
canvas.addEventListener(\(dqpointermove\(dq, (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (e.persistentDeviceId && pointerToColorMap.has(e.persistentDeviceId)) {
    \f[B]const\f[R] pointerColor = pointerToColorMap.get(e.persistentDeviceId);
    \f[I]// Do some inking on the <canvas>\f[R]
  }
});
.EE
